The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport
		 Tuesday, February 10, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	New Delhi: Indian custodian Helen Mary not only withstood the onslaught of the Japanese strikers, but also the pain of a fractured little finger for the entire 70 minutes in the Asia Cup hockey summit clash which India won 1-0 on Sunday.				 																																	I sustained a injury to my little finger five minutes before the match during the warm up, Mary said here on Monday. Since I had warmed up, I could keep the tempo but once the match was over I started to feel that something was really wrong and hence went for an x-ray, she said.				 																																	According to the x-ray report, Mary had sustained a fracture in her little finger. It will now take about a month to recover, she added.				 																																	Meanwhile, the international hockey federation (Fih) has agreed to nominate two training centres in India as high performance coaching centres, Indian womens hockey federation general secretary Amrit Bose said on Monday. 				 																																	Tunis: Senegal striker El Hadji Diouf has been banned for three international matches by the Confederation of African Football (CAF) following his teams stormy African Nations Cup quarter final defeat to Tunisia on Saturday, a tournament spokesman said on Monday.				 																																	Diouf, who carried out a running verbal battle with officials and opposing players throughout the latter part of the game, was accused of violent conduct. The ban will take effect from the beginning of the qualifying campaign for the 2006 World Cup, which gets underway in June.				 																																	Zagreb: Former Wimbledon champion Goran Ivanisevic is to make one final attempt at returning to competitive tennis this week after being sidelined for eight months through injury.				 																																	The big-serving Croat, who won at the All England Club in 2001, will play his first match at the ATP championship in Milan on Tuesday and has also been granted a wild card for the world indoor tournament in Rotterdam later this month.				 																																	This is definitely my last attempt to return, the 32-year-old told Mondays edition of the Jutarnji List newspaper. I had to give myself one more chance.				 																																	New Delhi: Indian grapplers put up an impressive performance to win one gold and one silver medal in the Dave Schuitz Memorial international wrestling tournament in Colorado Springs. The meet was held from Friday to Sunday.				 																																	Both the medals came in the Greco Roman bouts with Mukesh Khatri bagging gold in the 55kg and Gurbinder Singh claming silver in the 66kg category, a Wrestling Federation of India release said on Monday. 				 																																	London: Worcestershire are keen to sign up Australian paceman Andy Bichel for next season to replace the departing South African Nantie Hayward.				 																																	Hayward enjoyed a successful first season with the County, taking 67 wickets as they gained promotion to Division I of the County Championship. But the South African had not confirmed he would be returning to Worcestershire for a second campaign, and now the County is stepping up its efforts to get Bichel. 				 																																	Sydney: Multiple Olympic trap shooting champion Michael Diamond is to get a second chance to qualify for this years Athens Games after Australian officials agreed to bend the rules.				 																																	Diamond, who won gold at the Atlanta and Sydney Olympics, missed the first round of selection trials in January. Sport on Screen Soccer: Premier League highlights from 5 pm  on ESPN 
